Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. Defendant Deangelo F Smith in court with Attorney Joseph Smith.   District Attorney's Office Law Intern Katrina Seipel appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant enters a guilty plea to Count #1.  Court performs plea colloquy and finds Defendant guilty of Count #1.  State gives sentencing recommendations.  Attorney Smith makes statements regarding sentencing.  Defendant makes statements.  Court sentences the Defendant to the following:

COUNT #1:  WITHHELD SENTENCE

TERM OF PROBATION:  2 YEARS (1 day credit, if revoked)    **TRANSFER ALLOWED TO MILWAUKEE COUNTY** 

CONDITIONS OF PROBATON:  
____AODA Assessment and follow through with any treatment recommended;
____Absolute Sobriety;  Random U.A.'s ; 
____No Use or Possession of alcohol or illegal drugs/drug paraphernalia 
____No Use or Possession of prescription drugs without a valid prescription;
____Any valid prescription drugs must be taken only in the manner in which they are 
prescribed/sign releases.
____Inform Agent of all prescriptions
____Follow through with any treatment and/or counseling recommended by Agent;
____Maintain employment and/or combination of schooling 
____DNA sample to be provided if not yet previously done 

COSTS:  $268.00 & $250.00 DNA surcharge (to be paid out of cash bail posted ($500.00) and remainder due as a condition of probation)

CONDITION TIME:  120 Days, Non-working hours with standard release conditions,  LAST 100 DAYS STAYED - to be used at agent's discretion - Defendant to report to Huber facility by 3/18/16 by 5:00 p.m.  - May be served in Milwaukee County 

Felony Warnings, Voting Rights and Firearms Warnings provided to defendant
